.docname {Setting Up the Environment}
.include {docs}

Welcome to the CrowdVision developer setup guide. Because CrowdVision is a multi-service architecture with real-time sockets, push notifications, and AI capabilities, getting the local environment running requires setting up several databases, environment variables, and cryptographic secrets. 

Don't worry—we've provided scripts to automate the hardest parts.

---

## 🛠️ 1. Prerequisites

Before cloning the repository, ensure your local machine has the following tools installed:

*   **Node.js** (v18+ recommended)
*   **Docker & Docker Compose** (For running the isolated databases and services)
*   **Python 3.10+** (Required for the `agent-service`)
*   **Git**
*   **A local Kubernetes cluster & kubectl** (If you plan to deploy via k8s)

Once you have cloned the repository, install the monorepo dependencies. CrowdVision uses Lerna to manage workspace packages.

.code lang:{bash}
    git clone https://github.com/NickGhignatti/crowd-vision.git
    cd crowd-vision
    npm install

---

## 🔐 2. Environment Variables & Secrets

Microservices require secrets to communicate securely, encrypt tokens, and send push notifications. **Never commit `.env` files to version control.** 

Create a `.env` file in the root of your project. Below is the master template of required variables:

.code lang:{bash}
    # --- CORE SECRETS ---
    # The master key used by Auth, Twin, and Notification services to sign/verify JWTs
    JWT_SECRET=your_super_secure_random_string_here

    # --- DATABASES ---
    # Used by docker-compose.dbs.yml
    AUTH_DB_URI=mongodb://localhost:27017/auth
    TWIN_DB_URI=mongodb://localhost:27018/twin
    SENSOR_DB_URI=mongodb://localhost:27019/sensor
    NOTIFICATION_DB_URI=mongodb://localhost:27020/notification
    REDIS_URI=redis://localhost:6379

    # --- WEB PUSH (VAPID) ---
    VAPID_PUBLIC_KEY=
    VAPID_PRIVATE_KEY=
    VAPID_SUBJECT=mailto:admin@yourdomain.com

    # --- AI AGENT SERVICE ---
    # Required for the Python LLM Agent
    GEMINI_API_KEY=your_google_gemini_key
    # DEEPSEEK_API_KEY=your_deepseek_key_here (if using DeepSeek)

.box type:{warning}
    **Security Note:** All microservices that share the `JWT_SECRET` must have the exact same string in their environment context, otherwise cross-service authorization (Stateless Trust) will fail with a `401 Unauthorized`.

### Generating VAPID Keys
To securely send web push notifications, you need a VAPID key pair. Do not invent these manually. We have provided a utility script to generate cryptographically sound keys.

Run the following command and copy the output into your `.env` file:

.code lang:{bash}
    node scripts/vapid.js

---

## 🐳 3. Spinning Up via Docker Compose (Local Dev)

If you are developing locally without Kubernetes, you generally want to run the databases in Docker, but keep the Node/Vue services running directly on your host machine for hot-reloading.

### Start the Databases
This command spins up the isolated MongoDB instances for Auth, Twin, Sensor, and Notifications, along with the Redis message broker.

.code lang:{bash}
    docker-compose -f docker-compose.dbs.yml up -d

*Verify they are running by typing `docker ps`.*

### Start the Services
With your databases running, you can launch the application services via your local Node environment for hot-reloading across the monorepo:

.code lang:{bash}
    npx lerna run dev --parallel

---

## 🌱 4. Bootstrapping the System (Provisioning)

With empty databases, you cannot log in. You need an initial Global Admin account and a default Domain to access the dashboard.

We have provided provisioning scripts to seed your local databases safely.

.code lang:{bash}
    # Provision the initial Admin account and default Domain
    node scripts/provision.js
    
    # Or, if you need to create additional admin users manually:
    node scripts/admin.js create --email admin@local.dev --password securepass

*(Note: If you are working on the Python AI Agent, you can also use `python seed.py` within the `server/agent-service/` directory to load initial RAG context).*

---

## ☸️ 5. Kubernetes Deployment

If you are deploying CrowdVision to a local or remote Kubernetes cluster, you must apply the configurations in a specific order to ensure secrets and databases are available before the microservices spin up.

### Step 1: Create the Namespace & ConfigMaps
First, isolate the environment and apply non-sensitive configuration data.

.code lang:{bash}
    kubectl apply -f k8s/namespace.yml
    kubectl apply -f k8s/configmaps/

### Step 2: Inject Secrets
Because we never commit secrets to the repository, you must create a Kubernetes Secret manually using the values from your `.env` file. Assuming your deployments look for a secret named `crowd-vision-secrets` in the `crowd-vision` namespace, run:

.code lang:{bash}
    kubectl create secret generic crowdvision-secrets \
      --namespace=crowdvision \
      --from-literal=JWT_SECRET="your_super_secure_random_string_here" \
      --from-literal=VAPID_PUBLIC_KEY="your_vapid_public" \
      --from-literal=VAPID_PRIVATE_KEY="your_vapid_private" \
      --from-literal=VAPID_SUBJECT="mailto:admin@yourdomain.com" \
      --from-literal=GEMINI_API_KEY="your_google_gemini_key"

### Step 3: Start Stateful Services (Databases)
Spin up Mongo and Redis. Wait for these pods to be fully `Running` before proceeding.

.code lang:{bash}
    kubectl apply -f k8s/stateful/
    kubectl get pods -n crowdvision -w

### Step 4: Start Microservices & Ingress
Once the databases are ready and the secrets are injected, deploy the backend services, the frontend client, and the ingress controller routing.

.code lang:{bash}
    kubectl apply -f k8s/deployments/
    kubectl apply -f k8s/ingress.yml

### Accessing the Platform
Depending on your cluster setup and Ingress configuration, the platform will be available at the host defined in your `k8s/ingress.yml` file (e.g., `http://crowdvision.local`). Ensure your local `/etc/hosts` file maps the ingress host to your cluster's IP.